  • August 31, 2020 by Kessler DuPont, Organizer
    Monthly Recap | August 2020

    Greetings, Rocketeers!

    We’re adjusting the two-week interval on updates to be monthly. Here’s the recap for the month of August:

    Through our donation of compute power to Folding at Home, we helped to complete the first and second COVID Moonshot sprints, and the third is well underway. These sprints are designed to look for compounds that will combat COVID-19. We’re still waiting on the results of the finished sprints, which should be coming in next month's update. The third sprint is focused on compounds that are derivatives of molecules like benzotriazole, which you can read more about here: (https://foldingathome.org/2020/08/24/covid-moonshot-sprint-3/)

    Team Members Kessler & Luke had a chance to link up in person near the beginning of the month to install a new power supply unit that will reduce electricity costs. With this increased efficiency, we can support more projects in the future!

    Our point counter hit 180,000,000 before the end of the month, and the 200,000,000 milestone is right around the corner!

    Thanks again for all your support!

    Reminder: You can always see our real-time mission status at this website:
    https://dupontinquiries.github.io/github
  • August 7, 2020 by Kessler DuPont, Organizer
    Why We Fight | Mission Update on Friday, August 7

    Greetings, Rocketeers!

    Let’s take the time to remember why we fight: Luke Barden, one of our six team members said, “my friend recently contracted coronavirus. Although it didn’t cost him his life, the same cannot be said for thousands of Americans. That’s why I choose to fight.”

    And fight we will! We’ve made so much progress with compute power that you have helped to provide us, and now we rank in the top 0.4% of contributors. Copy and paste this web address to see the Folding at Home rankings: folding.extremeoverclocking.com.

    If you’ve been following the live tracker over on my website, you may have noticed on a couple of days that the point counter was stagnant. This downtime was due to power outages from Hurricane Isaias. Through it all, the team and I have been flexible, and we were even able to capitalize on the downtime.

    How were we able to do this, you may ask? Well, we’ve been in touch with the Folding community, and we’ve been adjusting to new top-priority projects as we enter the next phase of analysis. Thanks to the modular capabilities of The Rocket, I was able to make some modifications to the computer that tune it to the current task at hand. These mods will give us a 25% increase in productivity!

    Our contributors have been the backbone of this, and we’d like to ask you all to share our mission again to remind people that they too can help.

    Many thanks,

    Kessler DuPont

    Reminder: You can always see our real-time mission status at this website:
    https://dupontinquiries.github.io/github
  • July 22, 2020 by Kessler DuPont, Organizer
    Shattering Records | Mission Update Wednesday, July 22

    Greetings, Rocketeers!

    While some early vaccine candidates look promising enough to get us out of our houses, we still have a lot to learn about the coronavirus. The Folding at Home exascale supercomputer, the largest in the world, is coordinating the resources of computers like The Rocket to shatter records and learn more about the virus. Recently, an unprecedented 0.1-second simulation of the viral proteome has allowed researchers to see something even the best microscopes cannot and understand how the Coronavirus reshapes itself to evade our immune response. These results will almost certainly reap very real benefits as scientists use this information to strengthen current treatments and develop new COVID-19 therapeutics.

    You can read the full paper here: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.06.27.175430v1

    Again, we’d like to thank those who have already contributed and would like to remind you to please share our mission on Facebook and other social media platforms. We need more donations to continue the fight.

    Many thanks from the whole team!

    PS: You can always see our real-time mission status at this website:
    https://dupontinquiries.github.io/

  • July 1, 2020 by Kessler DuPont, Organizer
    3,000,000 and Counting | Mission Update on Wednesday, July 1

    Greetings, Rocketeers!

    The number 3,102,909 is a good measurement of our scientific contribution. Our hardware choice gives us the capability to contribute more than even the top gaming computers, and our prioritization of folding ensures that we deliver our maximum.

    In the past 2 days, we have risen to rank in the top 5% of all participants. We have helped researchers by providing computation for a variety of simulations related to COVID-19. We have rendered ion channels, ssRNA, and more. In the time it took me to write this, we earned another 20,000 points. A live points tracker will be available on my website so that anyone can see how we’re doing: https://dupontinquiries.github.io/

    Some of our supporters have asked about the data we provide and how it is used by scientists in the fight against COVID-19. Our work on simulating the interactions of hundreds of millions of atoms that form the proteins and sugars of the Coronavirus allows scientists to see the complex dynamics of the active virus. This is something that is not possible with current microscope technology.

    As cases spike in the US, our mission becomes even more important. We still need donations of any amount!

    TL;DR
    We are making a difference for researchers looking to fight the Coronavirus! We still need donations in order to hit our goal of $9271.

    Thanks again for all the support,

    Kessler DuPont

  • June 9, 2020 by Kessler DuPont, Organizer
    Why so expensive? | Mission Update on Tuesday, June 9

    Hello, current & potential supporters,

    My name is Kessler DuPont, and I’m the founder of this initiative to fight COVID-19. Today, I’d like to explain in detail why we are shooting for $9271 dollars.

    Why $9271?
    When designing a computer with protein folding in mind, we have to keep in mind the computational characteristics of protein folding.

    Folding runs fastest when computation becomes parallelized, and the GPU has become the platform that researchers use to off-load parallelizable operations.

    ECC memory, or Error Correction Code memory, is another key component of a computer when data is mission-critical. ECC Memory sticks are, however, more expensive than their non-ECC counterparts.

    These mission-critical components make up a significant portion of our goal. The rest is for other parts of the computer, like the CPU, motherboard, case, and power supply unit. When all these parts work together, we’ll have a formidable computer.
    ‌
    TL;DR
    Powerful mission-critical parts will be more expensive, but they will provide us with fast, reliable computational power that we can use for our mission of protein folding.

    Thanks again for all the support,

    Kessler DuPont

Kessler DuPont is organizing this fundraiser.
Hello, potential contributor!


We are a team of undergraduate engineering students at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in Troy, New York, looking to fight in the battle against COVID-19.  Our strategy focuses on high-performance computing, and we need your help!


We are joining the Stanford Folding@home (FAH) effort to simulate protein folding, computational drug design, and other types of molecular dynamics.  This effort could lead to a new vaccine or treatment for COVID-19.  With a powerful computer dedicated to this task, we can help in the fight against this disease and the next one.


Our goal is to raise $9,271 for high-performance computer components that our team will assemble and tune for the FAH effort.


Any proceeds raised above our goal will go to No Kid Hungry to ensure kids can eat during the Coronavirus crisis.


After we have defeated this disease, our team will repurpose the computer for AI research on Rensselaer’s campus.


We thank you in advance for your contribution of any amount, and appreciate your support of this engineering initiative to tackle COVID-19!


Thanks from the whole team,


Kessler, Jack, Michael, SJ, Luke, & Andrew
